subSubSection.paragraph:
Males monorchic, gonad left of the intestine. Spicules paired, curved, noncephalated. Gubernaculum with well-developed dorsocaudal apophyses. Large sperm cells with fibrillar appearance present, arranged in a single row. Sperm cells were not considered a diagnostic feature in the cladistic analysis of the family Xyalidae but might appear of taxonomic significance in the future. This feature is present also in other monhysterids (e.g.
Terschellingia glabricutis
).
